Add a fail-closed startup guard so production refuses to boot with default/weak secrets. In backend/app/core/config.py add a Pydantic v2 model_validator on Settings:

    from pydantic import model_validator

    _DEV_SECRET = "dev-insecure-secret-change-me"

    @model_validator(mode="after")
    def _guard_production_secrets(self) -> "Settings":
        if self.env.lower() == "production":
            problems = []
            if self.app_secret == self._DEV_SECRET or len(self.app_secret) < 32:
                problems.append("APP_SECRET must be set to a strong (>=32 char) non-default value")
            if self.admin_password == "admin":
                problems.append("ADMIN_PASSWORD must be set to a non-default value")
            if problems:
                raise ValueError("Insecure production config: " + "; ".join(problems))
        return self

This makes Settings() (config.py:101) raise at import/boot in production when secrets are defaults/weak, blocking the breach. (Equivalently the assertion can live in main.py's lifespan before bootstrap, but a model_validator fails earlier and covers all import paths.) Keep dev defaults for non-production so local dev is unaffected.

